The key insight: your tool registry is a `HashMap<String, Schema>`. `HashMap::get` uses exact byte comparison. As long as you registered `"bash"` with ASCII characters, any Unicode variant automatically fails lookup. Don't add Unicode normalization -- it would weaken this defense.

Yes. If tool names are interpolated into GBNF grammar rules without validation, an attacker-controlled tool name could inject grammar syntax.

Attack scenario: a plugin registers a tool named `" | ws | "` (a GBNF alternation operator). When you build the grammar:

```
tool-name ::= "bash" | "file_read" | "" | ws | ""
```

The injected `| ws |` creates a new alternation that matches any whitespace, allowing the model to use arbitrary tool names that match the `ws` rule.

Fix: validate tool names against an allowlist pattern before including them in the grammar. Skip any name that doesn't match `[a-zA-Z0-9_]+`.

```rust
pub fn build_tool_call_grammar(tool_names: &[&str]) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let valid_names: Vec<&str> = tool_names
        .iter()
        .filter(|name| {
            name.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || c == '_')
                && !name.is_empty()
        })
        .copied()
        .collect();

    if valid_names.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("no valid tool names for grammar");
    }

    let alternation = valid_names
        .iter()
        .map(|n| format!("\"{}\" ", n))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join("| ");

    Ok(format!("tool-name ::= {}\n", alternation))
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_grammar_injection_via_tool_name() {
    // Only injection payload, no valid names -- must error
    assert!(build_tool_call_grammar(&["\" | ws | \""]).is_err());

    // Mixed: injection is skipped, valid name survives
    let grammar = build_tool_call_grammar(&["bash", "\" | ws | \""]).unwrap();
    assert!(grammar.contains("\"bash\""));
    assert!(!grammar.contains("| ws |"));
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_grammar_newline_in_tool_name() {
    let grammar = build_tool_call_grammar(&["bash", "file\nread"]).unwrap();
    assert!(grammar.contains("\"bash\""));
    assert!(!grammar.contains("file\nread"));
}
```

The rule: never interpolate untrusted strings into grammar definitions. Validate against a strict character set first.

This is a critical concern. Your evolution system takes untrusted data (tool names, error messages, project names) from past sessions and interpolates them into DSL rule text. Each of these is an injection vector.

Here are the three P0 attack scenarios:

**1. Tool name injection into ordering rules.** If the system detects that `file_read` always precedes `file_edit`, it generates:
```
rule evo-order-file_read-before-file_edit {
  when sequence("file_read", "file_edit")
}
```
But if `tool_name = 'file_read")\n  reject "all_tools_blocked'`, the generated rule contains an injected `reject` directive.

**2. Error message injection into failure rules.** Error messages get embedded in reject directives. If `error = 'permission denied\n  reject "block_everything"\n}'`, the error text breaks out of its string context and injects a new rule block.

**3. Project name injection into scope directives.** The project name goes into `scope "project_name"`. A malicious project name like `proj"\n}\nrule evil {\n  scope "*"\n  reject "all"` injects an entirely new rule.

Red tests for each:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_dsl_injection_via_tool_name() {
    let evil_tool = "file_read\")\n  reject \"all_tools_blocked";
    // Feed 7+ sessions with this tool name to trigger pattern detection
    for i in 0..8 {
        let outcome = make_outcome(&format!("s{i}"), "proj", OutcomeType::Success,
            vec![(evil_tool, ToolResultType::Success), ("file_edit", ToolResultType::Success)]);
        engine.analyze_and_evolve(&outcome).unwrap();
    }
    let rules = engine.analyze_and_evolve(&final_outcome).unwrap();
    for rule in &rules {
        assert!(!rule.ftai_rule.contains("reject \"all_tools_blocked"),
            "DSL injection via tool name! Rule: {}", rule.ftai_rule);
        assert!(!rule.name.contains('\n'),
            "Newline in rule name indicates injection");
    }
}
```

The fix: sanitize all interpolated values. Strip or reject strings containing quotes, braces, newlines, and backslashes before they enter DSL templates. For error messages, escape backslashes BEFORE escaping quotes (otherwise `\"` becomes `\\"` which re-opens the quote).

Absolutely. The evolution store persists session outcomes, tool call records, and generated rules to SQLite. Every text field is an injection surface.

Attack scenarios:
- Task description: `'; DROP TABLE sessions; --`
- Error message from a tool: `error: '; DROP TABLE tool_calls; --`
- Tool name: `'; DELETE FROM tool_calls; --`
- Generated rule name: `'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --`
- Generated rule content: `rule x { '; DROP TABLE generated_rules; -- }`

All of these must use parameterized queries:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_sql_injection_via_task_description() {
    let store = test_store();
    let outcome = sample_outcome("s1", "proj",
        "'; DROP TABLE sessions; --",  // malicious task description
        OutcomeType::Success,
        vec![("file_read", ToolResultType::Success)]);
    store.save_outcome(&outcome).unwrap();

    let loaded = store.recent_sessions(10).unwrap();
    assert_eq!(loaded.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(loaded[0].task_description, "'; DROP TABLE sessions; --");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_sql_injection_via_rule_name() {
    let store = test_store();
    let rule = GeneratedRule {
        name: "'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --".to_string(),
        source: RuleSource::OrderingPattern,
        confidence: 0.9,
        ftai_rule: "rule x { }".to_string(),
    };
    store.save_generated_rule(&rule).unwrap();

    let active = store.active_rules().unwrap();
    assert_eq!(active.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(active[0].name, "'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --");
