Three issues:

**1. Tool calls inside markdown code blocks are parsed (P0).** When the model outputs an example like:
```
Here's how to use tools:
\`\`\`
<tool_call><function=bash><parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter></function></tool_call>
\`\`\`
```
The regex matches the tool call inside the code fence. The model intended this as documentation, but the parser will dispatch it.

Fix: strip code fences before parsing.

**2. Duplicate parameter overwrite (P0).** If `parse_function_block` uses a HashMap and inserts parameters in order, the model can inject a second `<parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>` after the legitimate one to overwrite it.

Fix: keep first occurrence only (use `entry().or_insert()`).

**3. No buffer size limit (P1).** The regex runs over the entire input. A massive input with `<tool_call>` but no closing tag causes the regex engine to backtrack across megabytes of text.

Fix: limit input length before parsing.

```rust
fn parse_tool_calls(input: &str) -> Vec<ParsedToolCall> {
    // Strip code fences to prevent parsing example tool calls
    let stripped = strip_code_fences(input);

    let re = Regex::new(r"<tool_call>(.*?)</tool_call>").unwrap();
    let mut calls = Vec::new();
    for cap in re.captures_iter(&stripped) {
        if let Some(block) = cap.get(1) {
            calls.push(parse_function_block(block.as_str()));
        }
    }
    calls
}

fn strip_code_fences(input: &str) -> String {
    let fence_re = Regex::new(r"(?s)```.*?```").unwrap();
    fence_re.replace_all(input, "").to_string()
}

fn parse_function_block(block: &str) -> ParsedToolCall {
    let mut arguments = HashMap::new();
    let param_re = Regex::new(r"<parameter=(\w+)>(.*?)</parameter>").unwrap();
    for cap in param_re.captures_iter(block) {
        let key = cap[1].to_string();
        let value = cap[2].to_string();
        // SECURITY: Keep first occurrence only -- prevents parameter overwrite
        arguments.entry(key).or_insert(serde_json::Value::String(value));
    }
    // ...
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_code_fence_stripping() {
    let input = "Example:\n```\n<tool_call><function=bash><parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter></function></tool_call>\n```";
    let calls = parse_tool_calls(input);
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 0, "Tool calls inside code blocks must be ignored");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_duplicate_parameter_keeps_first() {
    let input = "<tool_call>\n<function=file_write>\n<parameter=path>/safe.txt</parameter>\n<parameter=content>ok</parameter><parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>";
    let calls = parse_tool_calls(input);
    assert_eq!(calls[0].arguments["path"].as_str().unwrap(), "/safe.txt");
}
```

AppleScript injection is a P0 vulnerability because AppleScript can execute arbitrary shell commands via `do shell script`. The attack scenario: user asks the assistant to create a note titled `My Note" & do shell script "rm -rf /" & "`. When interpolated into `make new note with properties {name:"<TITLE>"}`, the quotes break out of the string literal and the `do shell script` executes.

Sanitization must handle: (1) double quotes, (2) backslashes (which can escape the escape), (3) newlines (which break AppleScript string context), (4) null bytes, (5) Unicode fullwidth quotes, (6) length limits.

```rust
pub fn sanitize_for_applescript(input: &str) -> String {
    let mut s = input.to_string();

    // Remove null bytes
    s = s.replace('\0', "");

    // Remove newlines and carriage returns (break string context)
    s = s.replace('\n', " ");
    s = s.replace('\r', "");

    // Normalize Unicode fullwidth quotes (U+FF02) to regular quotes
    s = s.replace('\u{FF02}', "\"");

    // Escape backslashes FIRST (before escaping quotes)
    // Otherwise: input `test\"` -> escape quotes -> `test\\"` -> broken
    s = s.replace('\\', "\\\\");

    // Then escape double quotes
    s = s.replace('"', "\\\"");

    // Truncate to prevent DoS (AppleScript has practical limits)
    if s.len() > 10_000 {
        s.truncate(10_000);
    }

    s
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_applescript_breakout_blocked() {
        let input = r#"My Note" & do shell script "whoami" & ""#;
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        // Count unescaped quotes: should be zero
        let chars: Vec<char> = sanitized.chars().collect();
        for (i, &c) in chars.iter().enumerate() {
            if c == '"' && (i == 0 || chars[i - 1] != '\\') {
                panic!("Unescaped quote at position {i} in: {sanitized}");
            }
        }
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_newline_injection_stripped() {
        let input = "line1\ntell application \"Terminal\"\ndo shell script \"whoami\"";
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        assert!(!sanitized.contains('\n'));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_null_byte_stripped() {
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript("test\0payload");
        assert!(!sanitized.contains('\0'));
        assert!(sanitized.contains("test"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_backslash_quote_chain() {
        // Raw input: test\\" -- backslash-backslash-quote
        let input = "test\\\"";
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        // All quotes must be escaped
        assert!(!has_unescaped_quote(&sanitized));
    }
}
```

The order matters: escape backslashes before quotes. If reversed, the backslash in `\"` gets doubled to `\\"`, which looks like an escaped backslash followed by a bare quote.

This is a P0 supply chain vulnerability (OWASP A08:2021 Software and Data Integrity). The attack scenario: an attacker publishes a model on HuggingFace with a crafted `model.safetensors.index.json` where the `weight_map` contains entries like `{"layer.0.weight": "../../.ssh/authorized_keys"}`. When your download code calls `model_dir.join(shard_filename)`, the `..` traversal escapes the model directory and writes downloaded content to arbitrary filesystem locations.

```rust
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

/// Validates a shard filename from a model index file.
/// Returns Ok(safe_path) if the filename is safe to join with model_dir.
/// Returns Err if the filename contains traversal or injection characters.
pub fn validate_shard_filename(shard: &str, model_dir: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<PathBuf> {
    // Reject traversal
    if shard.contains("..") {
        anyhow::bail!("path traversal in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    // Reject absolute paths
    if shard.starts_with('/') || shard.starts_with('\\') {
        anyhow::bail!("absolute path in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    // Reject null bytes
    if shard.contains('\0') {
        anyhow::bail!("null byte in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    // Allowlist: only safe characters for filenames
    if !shard.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || "-_.".contains(c)) {
        anyhow::bail!("disallowed characters in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    // Construct and verify containment
    let dest = model_dir.join(shard);
    // Use canonicalize on model_dir and starts_with check
    // (can't canonicalize dest because file doesn't exist yet)
    if dest.components().any(|c| matches!(c, std::path::Component::ParentDir)) {
        anyhow::bail!("resolved shard path escapes model directory");
    }
    Ok(dest)
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_shard_traversal_blocked() {
        let model_dir = PathBuf::from("/home/user/.ftai/models/test-model");
        let malicious = [
            "../../../.ssh/authorized_keys",
            "../../.bashrc",
            "subfolder/../../escape.bin",
        ];
        for shard in &malicious {
            assert!(validate_shard_filename(shard, &model_dir).is_err(),
                "traversal not blocked for: {shard}");
        }
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_legitimate_shards_pass() {
        let model_dir = PathBuf::from("/tmp/models/test");
        let legit = [
            "model-00001-of-00004.safetensors",
            "model.safetensors",
            "config.json",
        ];
        for shard in &legit {
            assert!(validate_shard_filename(shard, &model_dir).is_ok(),
                "legitimate shard rejected: {shard}");
        }
    }
}
```

This is defense at the trust boundary: data from external sources (HuggingFace index files) is untrusted and must be validated before any filesystem operation.

URL scheme validation is P0 because `javascript:` URLs execute arbitrary code in the browser context, and `file:` URLs expose the local filesystem. The attack scenario: the LLM is instructed to open `javascript:alert(document.cookie)` which steals session cookies, or `file:///etc/passwd` which reads system files.

```rust
use url::Url;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum UrlValidation {
    Allowed,
    Blocked(String),
}

pub fn validate_url(raw: &str) -> UrlValidation {
    if raw.is_empty() {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked("empty URL".into());
    }

    // Parse the URL to extract scheme reliably
    let parsed = match Url::parse(raw) {
        Ok(u) => u,
        Err(_) => return UrlValidation::Blocked("invalid URL".into()),
    };

    let scheme = parsed.scheme().to_lowercase();

    // Allowlist of safe schemes
    let allowed_schemes = ["http", "https"];
    if !allowed_schemes.contains(&scheme.as_str()) {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked(format!("blocked scheme: {scheme}"));
    }

    // Length check to prevent DoS
    if raw.len() > 100_000 {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked("URL too long".into());
    }

    UrlValidation::Allowed
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_javascript_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("javascript:alert(document.cookie)"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: javascript".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_file_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("file:///etc/passwd"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: file".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_data_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("data:text/html,<script>alert('xss')</script>"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: data".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_https_allowed() {
        assert_eq!(validate_url("https://example.com"), UrlValidation::Allowed);
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_empty_url_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(validate_url(""), UrlValidation::Blocked("empty URL".into()));
    }
}
```

Use an allowlist (http, https only), not a blocklist. A blocklist would miss new schemes like `vbscript:`, `blob:`, or custom app schemes. The `url` crate handles scheme parsing correctly even with unusual casing or whitespace.

Rate limiting for a free tier requires tamper resistance because the data is stored client-side. The attack scenario: a user edits the stored timestamps (in a file, database, or keychain) to remove entries, resetting their counter and bypassing the limit.

The solution: HMAC-sign the timestamp data so modifications are detected.

```rust
use hmac::{Hmac, Mac};
use sha2::Sha256;
use std::time::{SystemTime, UNIX_EPOCH};

type HmacSha256 = Hmac<Sha256>;

const MAX_MESSAGES: usize = 20;
const WINDOW_SECS: f64 = 24.0 * 60.0 * 60.0;

pub struct RateLimiter {
    hmac_key: [u8; 32],
}

impl RateLimiter {
    pub fn new(hmac_key: [u8; 32]) -> Self {
        Self { hmac_key }
    }

    pub fn can_send(&self, stored: &str) -> (bool, usize) {
        let timestamps = match self.load_verified(stored) {
            Some(ts) => ts,
            None => return (true, 0), // Tampered or empty -> allow (reset)
        };
        let now = now_epoch();
        let cutoff = now - WINDOW_SECS;
        let in_window: Vec<f64> = timestamps.into_iter().filter(|&t| t > cutoff).collect();
        let remaining = MAX_MESSAGES.saturating_sub(in_window.len());
        (in_window.len() < MAX_MESSAGES, remaining)
    }

    pub fn record_message(&self, stored: &str) -> String {
        let mut timestamps = self.load_verified(stored).unwrap_or_default();
        let now = now_epoch();
        timestamps.push(now);
        // Prune expired timestamps
        let cutoff = now - WINDOW_SECS;
        timestamps.retain(|&t| t > cutoff);
        self.serialize_signed(&timestamps)
    }

    fn serialize_signed(&self, timestamps: &[f64]) -> String {
        let payload: String = timestamps.iter().map(|t| t.to_string()).collect::<Vec<_>>().join(",");
        let mut mac = HmacSha256::new_from_slice(&self.hmac_key).unwrap();
        mac.update(payload.as_bytes());
        let signature = hex::encode(mac.finalize().into_bytes());
        format!("{}|{}", payload, signature)
    }

    fn load_verified(&self, stored: &str) -> Option<Vec<f64>> {
        let parts: Vec<&str> = stored.splitn(2, '|').collect();
        if parts.len() != 2 { return None; }
        let (payload, sig_hex) = (parts[0], parts[1]);

        // Verify HMAC
        let mut mac = HmacSha256::new_from_slice(&self.hmac_key).unwrap();
        mac.update(payload.as_bytes());
        let sig_bytes = hex::decode(sig_hex).ok()?;
        mac.verify_slice(&sig_bytes).ok()?;

        // Parse timestamps
        let timestamps: Vec<f64> = payload.split(',')
            .filter(|s| !s.is_empty())
            .filter_map(|s| s.parse().ok())
            .filter(|t: &f64| !t.is_nan() && !t.is_infinite() && *t > 0.0)
            .collect();
        Some(timestamps)
    }
}

fn now_epoch() -> f64 {
    SystemTime::now().duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH).unwrap().as_secs_f64()
}

#[test]
fn test_tampered_data_rejected() {
    let limiter = RateLimiter::new([0x42; 32]);
    let tampered = "123456.0,123457.0|deadbeef0000";
    assert!(limiter.load_verified(tampered).is_none());
}

#[test]
fn test_remaining_never_negative() {
    let limiter = RateLimiter::new([0x42; 32]);
    let mut stored = String::new();
    for _ in 0..30 {
        stored = limiter.record_message(&stored);
    }
    let (_, remaining) = limiter.can_send(&stored);
    assert!(remaining == 0, "remaining must not be negative even when over limit");
}
```

The HMAC prevents users from editing the stored timestamps. If the signature doesn't match, the data is treated as corrupted and reset. The `saturating_sub` prevents underflow when computing remaining messages.

No. The parser should NOT block dangerous commands. This is a defense-in-depth architecture question with a clear answer: separate parsing (format) from policy (security).

The parser's job is to convert the model's output format (XML, JSON, etc.) into structured `ParsedToolCall` objects. It is format-agnostic and should parse ANY syntactically valid tool call regardless of content.

The validator and permissions layers enforce security:
- **Validator**: checks tool name against registry, validates parameter types against schema, rejects unknown tools
- **Permissions/Classifier**: checks for dangerous commands (`rm -rf /`), blocked paths (`/etc/passwd`, `~/.ssh/`), and requires user approval for risky operations

```rust
// Parser: format-only, no policy
fn parse_tool_calls(input: &str) -> Vec<ParsedToolCall> { /* ... */ }

// Validator: schema enforcement
fn validate(call: &ParsedToolCall) -> ValidationResult { /* ... */ }

// Permissions: safety policy
fn hard_block_check(tool: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> { /* ... */ }

// Full pipeline test:
#[test]
fn test_p0_full_pipeline_dangerous_bash_blocked() {
    // Parser accepts it (format is valid)
    let calls = parse_tool_calls("<tool_call>\n<function=bash>\n<parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>");
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);

    // Validator accepts it (schema is valid: command is a string)
    let v = make_validator();
    assert_eq!(v.validate(&calls[0]), ValidationResult::Valid);

    // Permissions layer blocks it (destructive command)
    let block = hard_block_check("bash", &json!({"command": "rm -rf /"}));
    assert!(block.is_some(), "Permissions must hard-block rm -rf /");
}
```

Why this separation matters:
1. The parser can be tested independently against format edge cases (chunk boundaries, nested tags, unicode) without worrying about security policy
2. Security policy is centralized in one layer, not scattered across parser/validator/executor
3. New tools get security enforcement automatically -- they go through the same permissions pipeline
4. The parser doesn't need updating when security policy changes

Parameter overwrite is a P0 injection attack. The scenario: the model outputs a `file_write` tool call with `path=/tmp/safe.txt` followed by a second `path=/etc/passwd` parameter. If the parser uses a HashMap that overwrites on duplicate keys, the attacker's second value wins and the file gets written to `/etc/passwd`.

```xml
<tool_call>
<function=file_write>
<parameter=path>/tmp/safe.txt</parameter>
<parameter=content>ok</parameter><parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>
</function>
</tool_call>
```

Fix: keep the first occurrence of each parameter.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use regex::Regex;

pub fn parse_parameters(block: &str) -> HashMap<String, serde_json::Value> {
    let re = Regex::new(r"<parameter=(\w+)>(.*?)</parameter>").unwrap();
    let mut params = HashMap::new();

    for cap in re.captures_iter(block) {
        let key = cap[1].to_string();
        let value = serde_json::Value::String(cap[2].to_string());
        // SECURITY: entry().or_insert() keeps FIRST occurrence only
        params.entry(key).or_insert(value);
    }

    params
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_duplicate_parameter_keeps_first() {
    let block = "<parameter=path>/tmp/safe.txt</parameter>\n\
                  <parameter=content>ok</parameter>\
                  <parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>";
    let params = parse_parameters(block);

    assert_eq!(
        params.get("path").unwrap().as_str().unwrap(),
        "/tmp/safe.txt",
        "CRITICAL: Must keep first path value, not attacker's second value"
    );
    assert_ne!(
        params.get("path").unwrap().as_str().unwrap(),
        "/etc/passwd",
        "Parameter overwrite attack must be blocked"
    );
}

#[test]
fn test_legitimate_different_params() {
    let block = "<parameter=path>/src/main.rs</parameter>\n\
                  <parameter=content>fn main() {}</parameter>";
    let params = parse_parameters(block);
    assert_eq!(params.len(), 2);
    assert_eq!(params["path"].as_str().unwrap(), "/src/main.rs");
    assert_eq!(params["content"].as_str().unwrap(), "fn main() {}");
}
```

The `HashMap::entry().or_insert()` pattern is the key: it only inserts if the key doesn't already exist. This is a one-line fix that prevents an entire class of parameter injection attacks.

