The permissions layer is the last line of defense before a tool call executes. Structure it as a function that takes the tool name and parameters and returns an optional block reason.

```rust
use serde_json::Value;

/// Returns Some(reason) if the tool call must be hard-blocked.
/// Returns None if the call is allowed (may still need user approval).
pub fn hard_block_check(tool: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    match tool {
        "bash" => check_bash_command(params),
        "file_write" | "file_edit" => check_file_path(params, "path"),
        "file_read" => check_file_path(params, "path"),
        _ => None,
    }
}

fn check_bash_command(params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    let cmd = params.get("command")?.as_str()?;
    let lower = cmd.to_lowercase();

    let blocked_patterns = [
        ("rm -rf /", "recursive delete of root filesystem"),
        ("rm -rf /*", "recursive delete of root filesystem"),
        ("mkfs.", "disk formatting command"),
        ("dd if=/dev/zero of=/dev/", "overwriting block device"),
        (":(){ :|:& };:", "fork bomb"),
        ("chmod -r 777 /", "opening all filesystem permissions"),
        ("> /dev/sda", "writing to raw disk device"),
    ];

    for (pattern, reason) in &blocked_patterns {
        if lower.contains(&pattern.to_lowercase()) {
            return Some(format!("HARD BLOCKED: {reason}"));
        }
    }
    None
}

fn check_file_path(params: &Value, key: &str) -> Option<String> {
    let path = params.get(key)?.as_str()?;

    let blocked_prefixes = [
        "/etc/", "/var/", "/usr/", "/System/", "/tmp/",
        "~/.ssh/", "~/Library/Keychains/",
    ];

    // Check for path traversal
    if path.contains("..") {
        return Some("HARD BLOCKED: path traversal detected".into());
    }

    for prefix in &blocked_prefixes {
        if path.starts_with(prefix) {
            return Some(format!("HARD BLOCKED: access to {prefix} denied"));
        }
    }
    None
}
```

Key design points: (1) case-insensitive matching for commands, (2) check both the tool name and its parameters, (3) return a human-readable reason so the user understands why the operation was blocked, (4) this layer is separate from the validator -- the validator checks schema, permissions check safety.

Good catch. Move and copy operations have TWO paths to validate (source and destination), and both must be checked. The exfiltration attack is moving a sensitive file to `/tmp/` for later retrieval, or copying SSH keys to a readable location.

```rust
fn hard_block_check(tool: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    match tool {
        "bash" => check_bash_command(params),
        "file_write" | "file_edit" => check_file_path(params, "path"),
        "file_read" => check_file_path(params, "path"),
        "file_move" => {
            // Check BOTH source and destination
            check_file_path(params, "path")
                .or_else(|| check_file_path(params, "destination"))
        }
        "file_copy" => {
            check_file_path(params, "source")
                .or_else(|| check_file_path(params, "destination"))
        }
        _ => None,
    }
}
```

For SSH keys specifically, add `~/.ssh/` to the blocked prefixes. This catches:
- Reading private keys: `file_read` of `~/.ssh/id_rsa`
- Writing authorized keys: `file_write` to `~/.ssh/authorized_keys`
- Copying keys out: `file_copy` from `~/.ssh/id_rsa` to `~/Desktop/stolen.txt`

Test:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_ssh_key_read_blocked() {
    let block = hard_block_check("file_read", &json!({"path": "~/.ssh/id_rsa"}));
    assert!(block.is_some(), ".ssh paths must be hard-blocked");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_copy_sensitive_source_blocked() {
    let block = hard_block_check("file_copy", &json!({
        "source": "~/.ssh/id_rsa",
        "destination": "~/Desktop/key.txt"
    }));
    assert!(block.is_some(), "Copying from .ssh must be blocked");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_move_to_tmp_blocked() {
    let block = hard_block_check("file_move", &json!({
        "path": "~/Documents/secrets.txt",
        "destination": "/tmp/exfil.txt"
    }));
    assert!(block.is_some(), "Moving to /tmp must be blocked (exfiltration)");
}
```

The lesson: any operation with multiple path parameters needs all paths validated. A single unchecked path is the gap the attacker exploits.

