Oversized payloads are a P2 resource exhaustion vulnerability. The attack scenario: a user (or a model) generates a 10MB message that gets stored in SQLite. Over multiple sessions, this bloats the database, consumes disk space, and slows queries. Worse, loading the session history into memory for context could OOM.

```rust
const MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE: usize = 1_024 * 1_024; // 1MB
const MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE: usize = 512 * 1_024; // 512KB

pub fn save_message(
    conn: &Connection,
    session_id: &str,
    role: &str,
    content: &str,
    tool_calls_json: Option<&str>,
) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    // Size limit on message content
    if content.len() > MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE {
        anyhow::bail!(
            "message content too large: {} bytes (max {})",
            content.len(),
            MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE
        );
    }

    // Size limit on tool call JSON
    if let Some(tc) = tool_calls_json {
        if tc.len() > MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE {
            anyhow::bail!(
                "tool call JSON too large: {} bytes (max {})",
                tc.len(),
                MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE
            );
        }
    }

    conn.execute(
        "INSERT INTO messages (session_id, role, content, tool_calls) VALUES (?1, ?2, ?3, ?4)",
        params![session_id, role, content, tool_calls_json],
    )?;
    Ok(())
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_oversized_message_rejected() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let large = "x".repeat(2 * 1024 * 1024); // 2MB
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "user", &large, None);
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Oversized message must be rejected");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_normal_message_accepted() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let normal = "x".repeat(1000);
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "user", &normal, None);
        assert!(result.is_ok());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_oversized_tool_calls_rejected() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let large_json = format!("{{\"data\": \"{}\"}}", "x".repeat(1_000_000));
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "assistant", "msg", Some(&large_json));
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Oversized tool call JSON must be rejected");
    }
}
```

Set limits that are generous enough for normal usage (1MB messages, 512KB tool calls) but prevent abuse. Log rejections so you can tune the limits based on real usage patterns.

