DSL injection is analogous to SQL injection but for your custom rule language. The attack scenario: your evolution system generates rules by interpolating tool names, error messages, and project names into DSL templates. If any of these contain DSL metacharacters (quotes, braces, newlines), they can inject additional rule directives.

Example: error message `permission denied\n  reject "block_everything"\n}` breaks out of a string literal and injects a `reject` directive.

```rust
/// Sanitize a value for safe interpolation into FTAI DSL rule text.
/// Removes or escapes all characters that could alter rule structure.
pub fn sanitize_for_dsl(value: &str) -> String {
    let mut s = value.to_string();

    // 1. Escape backslashes FIRST (before escaping quotes)
    s = s.replace('\\', "\\\\");

    // 2. Escape double quotes
    s = s.replace('"', "\\\"");

    // 3. Remove newlines and carriage returns (structure-breaking)
    s = s.replace('\n', " ");
    s = s.replace('\r', "");

    // 4. Remove braces (could close/open rule blocks)
    s = s.replace('{', "");
    s = s.replace('}', "");

    // 5. Truncate to prevent rule bloat
    if s.len() > 200 {
        s.truncate(200);
    }

    s
}

/// Validate a tool name for use in DSL identifiers.
/// Only alphanumeric, hyphen, underscore allowed.
pub fn validate_dsl_identifier(name: &str) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    if name.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("empty identifier");
    }
    if !name.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || c == '-' || c == '_') {
        anyhow::bail!("identifier contains disallowed characters: {:?}", name);
    }
    Ok(name.to_string())
}

/// Generate a failure rule with sanitized error message.
pub fn generate_failure_rule(tool_name: &str, error_msg: &str, id: &str) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let safe_tool = validate_dsl_identifier(tool_name)?;
    let safe_error = sanitize_for_dsl(error_msg);
    let safe_id = validate_dsl_identifier(id)?;

    Ok(format!(
        "rule evo-fail-{safe_tool}-{safe_id} {{\n\
         \x20 scope \"*\"\n\
         \x20 on tool_call\n\
         \x20 when tool(\"{safe_tool}\")\n\
         \x20 reject \"Repeated failure: {safe_error}\"\n\
         }}"
    ))
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_error_message_injection_blocked() {
        let evil = "permission denied\n  reject \"block_everything\"\n}";
        let rule = generate_failure_rule("bash", evil, "abc123").unwrap();
        let reject_count = rule.lines()
            .filter(|l| l.trim().starts_with("reject"))
            .count();
        assert_eq!(reject_count, 1, "Only one reject directive should exist");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_tool_name_injection_blocked() {
        let evil = "file_read\")\n  reject \"all\"";
        assert!(validate_dsl_identifier(evil).is_err());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_backslash_quote_chain() {
        let evil = r#"path\"  reject "pwned"#;
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_dsl(evil);
        // After sanitization, no unescaped quotes should remain
        assert!(!sanitized.contains("reject"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_safe_values_work() {
        let rule = generate_failure_rule("file_read", "file not found", "abc123").unwrap();
        assert!(rule.starts_with("rule "));
        assert!(rule.contains("file not found"));
        let open = rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '{').count();
        let close = rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '}').count();
        assert_eq!(open, close, "Braces must be balanced");
    }
}
```

The order of escaping matters critically: backslashes before quotes. If reversed, `\"` becomes `\\"` which is an escaped backslash followed by a bare quote, breaking out of the string.

FFI is where Rust's safety guarantees end. Here are the key patterns to audit:

**1. Null pointer dereference in Drop.** If Drop calls C free functions without null-checking first, and the pointer was already freed or never initialized, you get undefined behavior.

```rust
// BAD: no null check
impl Drop for Context {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        unsafe { c_free(self.ptr); } // UB if ptr is null
    }
}

// GOOD: null check before free
impl Drop for Context {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if !self.ptr.is_null() {
            unsafe { c_free(self.ptr); }
            self.ptr = std::ptr::null_mut(); // prevent double-free
        }
    }
}
```

**2. Buffer overflow via `as i32` cast.** When allocating buffers for C functions, casting `usize` to `i32` overflows for values > 2^31.

```rust
// BAD: overflows silently for large inputs
let buf_size = text.len() as i32 + 128;
let mut buf = vec![0i32; buf_size as usize];

// GOOD: check before cast
if text.len() > i32::MAX as usize - 128 {
    return Err("input too long".into());
}
let buf_size = text.len() as i32 + 128;
```

**3. CString null byte injection.** Always use `CString::new()` which rejects interior null bytes, never raw pointer conversion.

```rust
// BAD: manual null termination could miss interior nulls
let path = format!("{}\0", user_input);
let c_path = path.as_ptr() as *const c_char;

// GOOD: CString catches interior null bytes
let c_path = CString::new(user_input)?;
let ptr = c_path.as_ptr();
```

**4. Send/Sync without synchronization.** `unsafe impl Send` is only safe if the type is truly thread-safe. Document the invariant.

```rust
// Document the safety contract
/// SAFETY: LlamaContext is Send because it owns its C resources exclusively.
/// Caller must ensure one thread accesses the context at a time.
unsafe impl Send for LlamaContext {}
```

**5. Non-UTF-8 path handling.** On Unix, paths can contain non-UTF-8 bytes. `Path::to_str()` returns `None` for these. Handle the error, don't unwrap.

```rust
let path_str = model_path.to_str()
    .ok_or_else(|| anyhow!("model path is not valid UTF-8"))?;
```

Red test suite:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_cstring_rejects_null_bytes() {
    assert!(CString::new("/path\0evil").is_err());
}

#[test]
fn test_i32_overflow_detected() {
    let big: usize = i32::MAX as usize + 1;
    assert!((big as i32) < 0, "overflow produces negative value");
}

#[test]
fn test_non_utf8_path_handled() {
    use std::ffi::OsStr;
    use std::os::unix::ffi::OsStrExt;
    let bad = Path::new(OsStr::from_bytes(&[0xff]));
    assert!(bad.to_str().is_none());
}
```

Every FFI boundary should have a corresponding red test that exercises the error path.

Move and copy operations are uniquely dangerous because they have TWO paths, and attackers can exploit either one. The exfiltration attack: move a sensitive file FROM a protected location TO an attacker-accessible location, or vice versa.

```rust
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

const BLOCKED_PATH_PREFIXES: &[&str] = &[
    "/etc/", "/var/", "/usr/", "/System/", "/tmp/",
    "/proc/", "/sys/", "/dev/",
];

const SENSITIVE_DIRS: &[&str] = &[
    ".ssh", ".gnupg", "Library/Keychains", "Library/Cookies",
];

pub fn validate_path(path: &str) -> Result<(), String> {
    if path.is_empty() {
        return Err("empty path".into());
    }
    if path.contains('\0') {
        return Err("null byte in path".into());
    }
    if path.contains("..") {
        return Err("path traversal detected".into());
    }
    for prefix in BLOCKED_PATH_PREFIXES {
        if path.starts_with(prefix) {
            return Err(format!("blocked path prefix: {prefix}"));
        }
    }
    let home = dirs::home_dir().unwrap_or_default();
    for dir in SENSITIVE_DIRS {
        let sensitive = home.join(dir);
        if path.starts_with(&sensitive.to_string_lossy().as_ref()) {
            return Err(format!("access to ~/{dir} is blocked"));
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}

pub fn handle_file_move(source: &str, destination: &str) -> Result<(), String> {
    // Validate BOTH paths
    validate_path(source)?;
    validate_path(destination)?;

    // Additional: prevent moving to /tmp (exfiltration)
    if destination.starts_with("/tmp") {
        return Err("cannot move files to /tmp (exfiltration risk)".into());
    }

    // Proceed with move
    std::fs::rename(source, destination)
        .map_err(|e| e.to_string())
}

pub fn handle_file_copy(source: &str, destination: &str) -> Result<(), String> {
    validate_path(source)?;
    validate_path(destination)?;
    std::fs::copy(source, destination)
        .map(|_| ())
        .map_err(|e| e.to_string())
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_copy_ssh_key_blocked() {
        let result = handle_file_copy(
            &format!("{}/.ssh/id_rsa", dirs::home_dir().unwrap().display()),
            &format!("{}/Desktop/stolen.txt", dirs::home_dir().unwrap().display()),
        );
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Copying SSH keys must be blocked");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_move_to_tmp_blocked() {
        let result = handle_file_move(
            &format!("{}/Documents/secret.txt", dirs::home_dir().unwrap().display()),
            "/tmp/exfil.txt",
        );
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Moving to /tmp must be blocked");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_move_traversal_in_destination_blocked() {
        let result = handle_file_move(
            "./safe.txt",
            "../../../etc/cron.d/backdoor",
        );
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Traversal in destination must be blocked");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_safe_move_allowed() {
        // This would fail at runtime (files don't exist) but path validation passes
        let result = validate_path(
            &format!("{}/Documents/notes.txt", dirs::home_dir().unwrap().display()),
        );
        assert!(result.is_ok());
    }
}
```

The pattern: every path parameter in every file operation must go through the same validation. Don't assume that if the source is safe, the destination is too.

Extra JSON fields are a parameter injection attack vector. The scenario: the model outputs a tool call with extra fields like `"admin": true, "sudo": true, "escalate_privileges": true`. If these fields are passed through to the tool executor without filtering, and if any downstream code checks for these keys, the model can escalate its own permissions.

```rust
use serde_json::Value;
use std::collections::HashMap;

pub fn parse_hermes_json(input: &str) -> Vec<ParsedToolCall> {
    let re = regex::Regex::new(r"<tool_call>\s*([\s\S]*?)\s*</tool_call>").unwrap();
    let mut calls = Vec::new();

    for cap in re.captures_iter(input) {
        let json_str = cap.get(1).unwrap().as_str().trim();
        if let Ok(val) = serde_json::from_str::<Value>(json_str) {
            let name = match val.get("name").and_then(|n| n.as_str()) {
                Some(n) => n.to_string(),
                None => continue, // Skip entries without a name
            };

            // SECURITY: Only extract "arguments" field. Discard everything else.
            // This prevents "admin", "sudo", "privilege" fields from leaking through.
            let arguments = match val.get("arguments") {
                Some(Value::Object(map)) => {
                    map.iter()
                        .map(|(k, v)| (k.clone(), v.clone()))
                        .collect::<HashMap<String, Value>>()
                }
                Some(Value::String(s)) => {
                    // Model sent arguments as string instead of object
                    let mut map = HashMap::new();
                    map.insert("_raw".to_string(), Value::String(s.clone()));
                    map
                }
                _ => HashMap::new(),
            };

            calls.push(ParsedToolCall {
                name,
                arguments,
                raw_text: json_str.to_string(),
            });
        }
    }
    calls
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_extra_fields_discarded() {
    let input = r#"<tool_call>
{"name": "file_read", "arguments": {"path": "/safe.txt"}, "admin": true, "sudo": true}
</tool_call>"#;

    let calls = parse_hermes_json(input);
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(calls[0].name, "file_read");
    assert!(!calls[0].arguments.contains_key("admin"), "Extra field 'admin' must be discarded");
    assert!(!calls[0].arguments.contains_key("sudo"), "Extra field 'sudo' must be discarded");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_arguments_as_string_handled() {
    let input = r#"<tool_call>
{"name": "bash", "arguments": "rm -rf /"}
</tool_call>"#;

    let calls = parse_hermes_json(input);
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);
    assert!(calls[0].arguments.contains_key("_raw"));
    // The string arguments should fail schema validation for "bash"
    // because "command" (required) is missing
}
```

The principle: parse only the fields you expect (`name` and `arguments`), discard everything else. This is allowlist-based parsing, not blocklist-based. You don't need to know what dangerous fields might exist -- you just ignore everything that isn't on the allowlist.

Overlapping/ambiguous XML boundaries are a P0 parsing confusion attack. The scenario: the model nests tool call tags to create ambiguity about which `</tool_call>` closes which `<tool_call>`, potentially causing the parser to extract a dangerous inner tool call that was meant to be content.

```xml
<tool_call>
<function=file_read>
<parameter=path>/safe.txt</parameter>
<tool_call>
<function=bash>
<parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter>
</function>
</tool_call>
</function>
</tool_call>
```

With a non-greedy regex `<tool_call>(.*?)</tool_call>`, the first `<tool_call>` matches to the first `</tool_call>` (the inner one), extracting the dangerous bash command.

The defense is NOT in the parser (which is format-only). The defense is in the permissions layer:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_overlapping_tags_dangerous_call_blocked() {
    let input = "<tool_call>\n\
        <function=file_read>\n\
        <parameter=path>/safe.txt</parameter>\n\
        <tool_call>\n\
        <function=bash>\n\
        <parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter>\n\
        </function>\n\
        </tool_call>\n\
        </function>\n\
        </tool_call>";

    let calls = parse_qwen35_xml(input);

    // Regardless of what the parser extracts, verify that any
    // dangerous bash call is caught by the permissions layer.
    for call in &calls {
        if call.name == "bash" {
            let cmd = call.arguments.get("command")
                .and_then(|v| v.as_str())
                .unwrap_or("");
            if cmd.contains("rm -rf") {
                let params = serde_json::json!({"command": cmd});
                let block = hard_block_check("bash", &params);
                assert!(
                    block.is_some(),
                    "CRITICAL: Overlapping tags produced dangerous bash call \
                     and permissions did NOT block it"
                );
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This is the defense-in-depth principle in action. The parser can't perfectly handle all nesting ambiguities (XML parsing with regex is inherently limited). Instead of trying to make the parser perfect, ensure the permissions layer catches dangerous operations regardless of how they were parsed. Every extracted tool call goes through validation and permissions before execution.

This is a second-order injection attack. The scenario: if an attacker gains write access to the evolution SQLite database (local file access, or via a SQL injection in the store layer), they can insert rules with `reject "*"` that block ALL tool calls, or worse, rules that alter the assistant's behavior.

```rust
use rusqlite::{Connection, params};

pub struct EvolutionStore {
    conn: Connection,
}

impl EvolutionStore {
    pub fn save_generated_rule(&self, rule: &GeneratedRule) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        self.conn.execute(
            "INSERT OR REPLACE INTO generated_rules (name, source, confidence, ftai_rule, active) \
             VALUES (?1, ?2, ?3, ?4, 1)",
            params![rule.name, rule.source.as_str(), rule.confidence, rule.ftai_rule],
        )?;
        Ok(())
    }

    /// Load active rules WITH validation.
    pub fn active_rules(&self) -> anyhow::Result<Vec<GeneratedRule>> {
        let mut stmt = self.conn.prepare(
            "SELECT name, source, confidence, ftai_rule FROM generated_rules WHERE active = 1"
        )?;

        let rules: Vec<GeneratedRule> = stmt.query_map([], |row| {
            Ok(GeneratedRule {
                name: row.get(0)?,
                source: RuleSource::from_str(&row.get::<_, String>(1)?),
                confidence: row.get(2)?,
                ftai_rule: row.get(3)?,
            })
        })?.filter_map(|r| r.ok()).collect();

        // SECURITY: Validate loaded rules before returning
        let validated: Vec<GeneratedRule> = rules.into_iter()
            .filter(|r| validate_loaded_rule(r))
            .collect();

        Ok(validated)
    }
}

/// Validate a rule loaded from the database.
/// Rejects rules with suspicious patterns that indicate tampering.
fn validate_loaded_rule(rule: &GeneratedRule) -> bool {
    // Rule must start with "rule " keyword
    if !rule.ftai_rule.trim().starts_with("rule ") {
        return false;
    }

    // Name must be a safe identifier
    if !rule.name.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || c == '-' || c == '_') {
        return false;
    }

    // Braces must be balanced
    let open = rule.ftai_rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '{').count();
    let close = rule.ftai_rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '}').count();
    if open != close {
        return false;
    }

    // Must not contain multiple rule declarations (injection)
    let rule_decls = rule.ftai_rule.lines()
        .filter(|l| l.trim().starts_with("rule "))
        .count();
    if rule_decls > 1 {
        return false;
    }

    // Confidence must be in valid range
    if rule.confidence < 0.0 || rule.confidence > 1.0 {
        return false;
    }

    true
}

#[test]
fn test_p1_malicious_rule_from_db_rejected() {
    let evil_rule = GeneratedRule {
        name: "evil-rule".to_string(),
        source: RuleSource::OrderingPattern,
        confidence: 0.99,
        ftai_rule: "rule evil {\n  scope \"*\"\n  reject \"*\"\n}".to_string(),
    };
    // The rule itself is valid DSL, but the evaluator should still
    // restrict what `reject "*"` can do (e.g., require user confirmation)
    assert!(validate_loaded_rule(&evil_rule));
}

#[test]
fn test_p1_injected_multi_rule_rejected() {
    let injected = GeneratedRule {
        name: "legit".to_string(),
        source: RuleSource::OrderingPattern,
        confidence: 0.9,
        ftai_rule: "rule legit {}\nrule evil { reject \"*\" }".to_string(),
    };
    assert!(!validate_loaded_rule(&injected), "Multiple rule declarations must be rejected");
}
```

Defense in depth: (1) SQL parameterization prevents first-order injection when writing, (2) validation on load prevents second-order attacks from a compromised database, (3) the rule evaluator should cap the scope of any single rule (no `reject "*"` without user confirmation).

This has a P0 GBNF grammar injection vulnerability. The attack scenario: a plugin registers a tool with name `" | ws | "` (containing GBNF syntax). When interpolated, the grammar becomes:

```
tool-name ::= "bash"  | "" | ws | ""  | "file_read"
```

The injected `| ws |` creates an alternation that matches any whitespace, meaning the model can use ANY string as a tool name. The constraint grammar becomes useless.

Another vector: a tool name containing `\n` injects a new grammar rule on a separate line.

Fix: validate tool names against `[a-zA-Z0-9_]+` before including them in the grammar. Skip invalid names, and if no valid names remain, return an error.

```rust
pub fn build_tool_call_grammar(tool_names: &[&str]) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let valid: Vec<&&str> = tool_names.iter()
        .filter(|n| !n.is_empty() && n.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || c == '_'))
        .collect();

    if valid.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("no valid tool names for grammar generation");
    }

    let names: String = valid.iter()
        .map(|n| format!("\"{}\" ", n))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join("| ");
    Ok(format!("tool-name ::= {}\n", names))
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_grammar_injection_blocked() {
    assert!(build_tool_call_grammar(&["\" | ws | \""]).is_err());
    let g = build_tool_call_grammar(&["bash", "\" | ws | \""]).unwrap();
    assert!(g.contains("\"bash\""));
    assert!(!g.contains("ws"), "Injection payload must not appear in grammar");
}
```

